    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1962-07-10T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1962-07-10T00:00:00-05:00" n="147"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d147">
                <head>147. Memorandum From President <persName corresp="#p_KJF2" type="from"
                        >Kennedy</persName> to Secretary of State <persName corresp="#p_RD3"
                        type="to">Rusk</persName>
                    <note n="0" type="source" xml:id="d147fn0">Source: <persName corresp="#p_KJF2"
                            >Kennedy</persName> Library, National Security Files, Subjects Series,
                        Balance of Payments and Gold, 6/62-3/63. Confidential. Copies were sent to
                            <persName corresp="#p_BGW1">George Ball</persName>, <persName
                            corresp="#p_HF5">Fowler Hamilton</persName>, and <persName
                            corresp="#p_BDE1">David E. Bell</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1962-07-10">July 10, 1962</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>I have held two reviews of the overseas expenditures of <gloss target="#t_AID1"
                        >AID</gloss> with Mr. <persName corresp="#p_HF5">Hamilton</persName>, his
                    Regional Directors and other members of his staff on June 21 and July 5
                        [6].<note n="1" xml:id="d147fn1">See <ref target="#d142fn1">footnote 1,
                            Document 142</ref>, and <ref target="#d144fn11">footnote 11, Document
                            144</ref>.</note> Under Secretary <persName corresp="#p_BGW1"
                        >Ball</persName> was present at the second of these meetings. Their purpose
                    was to make clear to those responsible for administering the <gloss
                        target="#t_AID1">AID</gloss> program how urgently they should pursue the
                    task of holding to the minimum the balance of payments drain consequent on
                        <gloss target="#t_AID1">AID</gloss> programs.</p>
                <p>All development loans are now tied to U.S. procurement. A large share of the
                        <gloss target="#t_AID1">AID</gloss> expenditures that create claims against
                    dollars arise from cash grants and local currency purchases. Many of these have
                    in the past been in response to crisis situations; recent examples are South
                    Vietnam and Argentina. I think it would be most helpful if you were to see that
                    the same sense of concern about the balance of payments impact of these programs
                    was transmitted to your geographic bureaus, which must appraise requests for
                    emergency funds.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_KJF2">
                            <hi rend="strong">John F. Kennedy</hi>
                        </persName>
                        <note n="2" xml:id="d147fn2">Printed from a copy that indicates <persName
                                corresp="#p_KJF2">Kennedy</persName> signed the original.</note>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
